Since the inception of this page and the podcast, we were informed that its longevity, as well as that of a page concerning the use of force by law enforcement, would be short-lived. However, not only have we persevered, but we have also flourished by shedding light on the aspects that the media, citizens, and even fellow officers tend to overlook, unless it is linked to a biased perspective based on race. We acknowledge that there are indeed police officers who engage in misconduct, but what we advocate for is a deeper understanding beyond the brief four-second video clips or sound bites that are saturated with ulterior motives. It is with immense pride that we showcase the other side of law enforcement on our podcast, featuring exceptional guests who provide insight into the noble responsibilities of wearing the badge. One of the most gratifying compliments we receive is when individuals express, "I had no idea about the challenges you face" or when they express their newfound interest in pursuing a career in law enforcement. We extend our heartfelt gratitude to all our past and future guests, as well as to all of you who have supported our page. @iamchiefchanel @coconutvybez @_echo_5_india_ @up.in.ny @instructor_blue @dr.michelle__nd @drvictoria.dc @prezchamp2 @blondeinblue72 @kat.b.9 @angel_of_faith84 @itsme_itsme_lexi @pourthefinest @customly_krystal @floridadefensivetraining @salutetheblue @circa_1993 @re12becca @code3dmv @shieldus_co @lawenforcement__ @fraulinek9 @latinheat_po #police #mrsofficer #blackofficers #chiefofpolice

"What gun? I don't see a gun," is what you're probably thinking. Over the past couple of days, we have received inbox messages stating that this page scares and traumatizes people. However, our intention is not to do so. Instead, we aim to engage the average civilian who only sees the media's spin on police matters. In my personal opinion, most departments do a poor job of educating the public about what we encounter on a daily basis and why we do or don't do certain things in certain situations. So, if the page offends you, please unfollow. We understand. But to those who genuinely want to gain a glimpse into reality, thank you for supporting the page and podcast. I was once that way at 18 years of age. I thought every cop was racist, believed everything the media said, didn't do any research on my own, and listened to what my friends said or thought because I wanted to fit in. However, my perspective changed when I witnessed a white Baltimore city cop harassing my white friend and calling him white trash. This incident made me realize that assholes come in all colors. While there are some bad cops with bad attitudes, the vast majority took the job because it is a calling. I encourage you to take a ride along, do your own research, and listen to a police scanner. You'll be surprised by who calls the police and for what reasons. 😒😂 And as always, thank you for supporting our page and our podcast. 23 years old. Let that sink in for a moment. A young black man defying the prevailing anti-police sentiment in today's world and taking action beyond his own self-interest. The law enforcement community has suffered a loss, but beyond that, we continue to lose honorable individuals who strive to live right and transform the prevailing narrative. The tag readers on the back of police cars are used to detect information on vehicle tags, such as stolen, carjacked, suspended registration, and other classified information. Depending on the agency and programming, these tag readers can pick up a lot of information. So if you get pulled over, it's sometimes likely your tags were flagged for a specific reason by various agencies.  #police #lawenforcement #policeofficer #k9 #tagreaders
